		<header class="comment-header">
			<p class="comment-author" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/Person">
				<img alt='' src='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/69f6b30f671a70379364a461e5d70b11?s=96&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/69f6b30f671a70379364a461e5d70b11?s=192&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-96 photo' height='96' width='96' loading='lazy'/><span class="comment-author-name" itemprop="name"><a href="https://twitter.com/jasonbrownNEWS" class="comment-author-link" rel="external nofollow" itemprop="url">Jason Brown</a></span>			</p>

			<p class="comment-meta"><time class="comment-time" datetime="2021-04-19T04:39:36-04:00" itemprop="datePublished"><a class="comment-time-link" href="https://fair.org/home/support-the-tropes/#comment-3189400" itemprop="url">April 19, 2021 at 4:39 am</a></time></p>		</header>

		<div class="comment-content" itemprop="text">
			
			<p>“The Jakarta Method: Washington’s Anticommunist Crusade and the Mass Murder Program that Shaped Our World” was a great cover story for one of the greatest resource grabs ever. </p>
<p>At the same time as the slaughter in Indonesia, arrangements were being made to secure vast resource wealth in West Papua. Decades later, West Papua still hosts the world&#8217;s biggest gold mine. Radiating outwards, hundreds of billions more in other minerals, forests, oil and gas. </p>
<p>Half a million indigenous deaths documented. A gap with neighbouring Papua New Guinea of six million people &#8211; sixty years ago both populations were about equal.  And they call it a &#8220;slow&#8221; genocide. </p>
<p>On a global scale though, like this article shows, the scale of the slaughter from resource grabbing becomes more blatant.  </p>
<p>Virtually every western administration has featured appointments from the same global corporations extracting $1.5 trillion in resources annually, from the &#8216;third&#8217; world to the &#8216;first&#8217; world. In return for about a quarter of a trillion in aid and &#8216;free&#8217; trade and &#8216;democracy&#8217;.</p>
<p>Meantime, about a trillion disappears into tax havens, each year.  </p>
<p>Follow the money?</p>
<p>It will be interesting to see what comes from a new US law ending secrecy around true owners of all companies. Will Justice be given sufficient resources to enforce the new laws exposing &#8216;ultimate beneficiaries&#8217; and holding them to, erm, account? Or just another data point joining myriad other policy failures to end systemic corruption.</p>
<p>&#8220;Love the tropes&#8221; captures all that sort of thing beautifully. Someone stop me before I start quoting Smedley Butler.</p>
		</div>

